@node "Read" "Read"
Read
====

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      This function allows to read the selected files (ascii).  A slider is
  on the right of screen.  On the right lower-corner, there are two numbers
  separated by a "/". The first one is the current line, and the second one
  is the number of  lines of the file.  Several buttons are located on  the
  bottom of the screen :

      - Print : print the file

      - Abort (short-cut key : "A") : quit the  text viewer, and  abort the
  current  operation.  For example,  if you  have selected  several  texts,
  Ordering will stop reading these texts.

      - Quit (short-cut key : "Q", "X" or "Esc") : quit the text viewer.

      - Top (short-cut key : "T"  or  Alt+arrow up  or  "7"  on the numeric
  keypad) : go to the top of the text.

      - Bottom (short-cut key : "B" or Alt+arrow down or "1" on the numeric
  keypad) : go  to the  bottom of the text.

      - Iconify (short-cut key : "I") : close the  window and the screen of
  the text viewer, and open a  little  window on the main program's screen.
  To come back to the text viewer,  press the right  mousebutton when  this
  window is active.  This option is only  available if the  text is read in
  background (if you double-click the file).

      - Line Up (short-cut key : arrow up  or  "8" on the numeric keypad) :
  scroll the text up, line by line.

      - Line Down (short-cut key : arrow down  or  "2"  on the numeric key-
  pad) : scroll the text down, line by line.

      - Goto Line (short-cut key : "G") : the program asks you to enter the
  number of the line where you want to go.

      - Page Up (short-cut key : "U" or Shift+arrow up  or "9" on the nume-
  ric keypad) : scroll the text up, page by page.

      - Page Down (short-cut  key : "D"  or Shift+arrow down or "3" on the
  numeric keypad) : scroll the text down, page by page.

      - Hexa/Ascii (short-cut  key : "H") : toggle  hexadecimal/ascii  dis-
  play.

      - Find... (short-cut key : "F" or "S") : search for a string.

      - Previous (short-cut  key : "P") :  the  program  searches  for  the
  string entered with "Find...", from the current line, and backward.

      - Next (short-cut  key : "N") : the  program searches for the  string
  entered with "Find...", from the current line, and forward.

      Moreover you can move the text left and right using the arrows or the
  "4" and "6" key on the numeric keypad.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Right mousebutton to quit :
      You may come  back  to the main program  just by  pressing  the right
  mousebutton.

  Immediate scrolling :
      When clicking  "Page Up" or "Page Down" button,  text will be redrawn
  immediately, without progressive scrolling.

  Find all occurrences :
      If a string searched for can be found sevaral times on the same line,
  it is found only once,  because when clicking the  "Next" button,  search
  restarts  from the  beginning  of next line.  Activating this option will
  make search restart immediately after the already found string.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      The "Find..." option uses the Boyer-Moore algorithm.  I think a better
  algorithm doesn't exist. It is all the more fast since the string is long.
  So please  compare it with other text viewers.  If you  find a faster one,
  please tell @{"me" LINK Address} about it.

@endnode


@node "HexRead" "Hexadecimal read"
Hexadecimal read
================

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      This  function is the  same as @{"Read" LINK Read},  but the  file is displayed  in
  hexadecimal.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Right mousebutton to quit :
      You may come back  to the  main program  just by  pressing  the right
  mousebutton.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      See @{"Read" LINK Read}.

@endnode


@node "Search" "Search string"
Search string
=============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Ordering  asks you to  type a  string  to search for  in the selected
  files and directories. If it is found, you may read the text and continue
  the search.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "Run" "Run"
Run
===

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Run selected files, with arguments that you may enter.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Runback :
      Executes programs in background.

  Output window :
      A window will be  opened  for each  launched  program.  Window may be
  defined with @{"Options" LINK Options} in the preferences editor.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "ExternalTool" "External tool"
External tool
=============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Allows to execute external programs with parameters.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Runback :
      Executes programs in background.

  Output window :
      A window will be  opened  for each  launched  program.  Window may be
  defined with @{"Options" LINK Options} in the preferences editor.

  Reread source directory :
      When execution is completed,  Ordering will read the source directory
  again.

  Reread destination directory :
      When  execution is  completed,  Ordering will  read  the  destination
  directory again.

  External tool :
      You should enter the name and the path of the  program to run and its
  parameters in this box. There are two little buttons on the right side of
  the box.  If you click the first one, you may select the tool with a file
  requester.  If you click the second one, a window will be opened.  A list
  of little strings is displayed.  Each one starts with "%".  When the tool
  is launched, they are replaced by what they represent.  Here are  several
  examples :

      - Imagine  you created a  button with the  "External tool"  function,
  with "C:Dir %sd" in the box, and the "Output window" option active. "%sd"
  means "source directory". When you press the button, "%sd" is replaced by
  the  current  source directory.  If it is "RAM:",  Ordering  will run the
  "C:Dir RAM:" command.

      - Now let's see  something more useful : how to list an LhA  archive.
  You may associate  to the @{"filetype" LINK FileTypes} "LHArc" the "External tool" function,
  with "C:LhA v "%dcf"" in the box,  and the "Output window" option active.
  %dcf means "double-clicked file".  If you double-click the "Ordering.lha"
  file, located in  the "DH0:Archives" directory,  Ordering will launch the
  "C:LhA v "DH0:Archives/Ordering.lha"" command. Please note that "%dcf" is
  in quotation marks.  This  avoids lots of  problems if the  path name has
  spaces.

      - Here is the way to extract  LhA archives : associate to the "LHArc"
  @{"filetype" LINK FileTypes} (right mousebutton  if you already have associated an action to
  this filetype), the "External tool" function, with "C:LhA x "%dcf" "%dd""
  in the box,  and the  "Output window" and  "Reread destination directory"
  options  active.  Imagine the   destination  directory is "RAM:".  If you
  double-click  the "Ordering.lha"  file  located  in  "DH0:Archives".  The
  "C:LhA x "DH0:Archives/Ordering.lha" "RAM:"" will be launched.  When this
  is completed, Ordering will read the destination directory again ("RAM:")
  in order to update it.

      - And now, how to create an LhA archive.  Create a @{"button" LINK Buttons} or a @{"menu" LINK Menus}
  item with the "External tool"  function, with  "C:LhA -r a "%fr" %ase" in
  the  box,  and the  "Output window"  option  active.  "%fr"  means  "file
  requester" and %ase means "all selected entries".  Imagine you select the
  "Disk.info" and  "System.info"  files in the  "DH0:" directory.  When you
  press the created button,  a file  requester will be opened.  Select your
  archive name. If you have selected the "RAM:Test.lha" file, Ordering will
  launch the "C:LhA -r a "RAM:Test.lha" DH0:Disk.info DH0:System.info" com-
  mand.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "Print" "Print"
Print
=====

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Print selected files.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      The device used may be edited with the preferences editor (@{"Options" LINK Options}).

@endnode


@node "PrintDir" "Print directory"
Print directory
===============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Print the contents of the directory, as it is displayed.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Print diskname :
      If this option is active, Ordering will print the path, the diskname,
  and the free size.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      The device used may be edited with the preferences editor (@{"Options" LINK Options}).

@endnode


@node "DiskCopy" "Copy a disk"
Copy a disk
===========

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Copies a disk. If the "Verify" option is active, each written track
  is read and compared with the buffer to write. It is much slower, but
  disk will be correctly copied.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "Format" "Format a device"
Format a device
===============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Formats disks, hard disks...

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      The  device is  formatted in  background.  You may  continue  to  use
  Ordering,  and  you  may also  format  other devices (try to do that on a
  peecee).

@endnode


@node "Relabel" "Relabel a volume"
Relabel a volume
================

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Allows to relabel one of the present devices.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "Install" "Install a disk"
Install a disk
==============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Allows to install a bootblock on disks.  You may load a @{"BBM library" LINK BBMLib},
  to install any bootblock.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      None.

@endnode


@node "About" "About Ordering"
About Ordering
==============

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Displays informations about  Ordering and its author (@{"me" LINK Address}).  The name
  of the public screen is also displayed.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      This  function is not  very  useful... You  should  rather  read  the
  @{"Important" LINK Important}, @{"Introduction" LINK Introduction} and @{"Author's address" LINK Address} paragraphs.

@endnode


@node "Iconify" "Iconify"
Iconify
=======

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Closes  the window and the screen,  then opens a little window on the
  Workbench screen. You may quit the program by closing the window, or come
  back to  the  usual  screen by  pressing the  right  mousebutton when the
  window is active.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

      None.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      Using this function allows to reduce memory  usage  if you don't need
  Ordering immediately.

@endnode


@node "ReadPrefs" "Reread preferences"
Reread preferences
==================

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Rereads the preferences file.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  File requester :
      To select the preferences file to load. If this option is not activa-
 ted, Ordering tries to load the "ENVARC:Ordering.prefs" file.  Note : this
 option is available only if reqtools.library is present.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      This option is very useful to create your own preferences.  Each time
  you save the preferences in the @{"preferences editor" LINK PreferencesEditor}, you should call this
  function.

      Warning : everything is  reinitialized.  Buffers,  selection  will be
  lost.

@endnode


@node "Quit" "Quit"
Quit
====

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}

      Quits Ordering.

@{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

  Confirm :
      The program asks if you really want to quit.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub}

      Don't forget to  create a command  to quit in  the @{"buttons" LINK Buttons} or in the
  @{"menus" LINK Menus}...

@endnode



@node "BBMLib" "BBM libraries"
BBM libraries
==============

      A BBM library is a file  created  by  Bootblock Manager (BBM),  which
  contains several bootblocks.  So you may install the bootblocks  that you
  want on your disks.

@endnode



